"response_text": "The mean deviation between agents' held environmental values and the implied values of their milk choices begins at 0.0000 at the initial time step. This initial equilibrium suggests a starting condition where consumer purchasing behavior aligns perfectly with their environmental perceptions. Over the first 13 time steps, this deviation increases rapidly, reaching a maximum value of 13.4756 at time step 13. This sharp rise indicates a growing disconnect between what consumers value environmentally and the environmental impact of the milk products they select. Statistically, the trend during the first 10 time steps is significant, with a slope of 2.840 in the initial window, confirming a structured shift rather than random fluctuation.\n\nFollowing the peak at time step 13, the metric stabilizes at a high level, fluctuating narrowly between approximately 13.41 and 13.45 for the remainder of the simulation. By the final time step, the value settles at 13.4186. Statistical analysis shows no significant trend in the later windows, indicating that the system has reached a steady state of misalignment. This persistent high deviation reflects the tension inherent in the model between strong established habits and evolving environmental perceptions. With an incumbent habit strength set to 10 and moderate social susceptibility, agents appear to struggle to adjust their purchasing choices to match their internal values, resulting in a sustained cognitive dissonance regarding the environmental implications of their consumption throughout the simulated period."
}

